{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti 11.74, as part of the penances prescribed for a Brahmana-slayer (one of the mahāpātakas or great sins, introduced at 11.71–72),** the text states that the offender **\"may sacrifice with a horse-sacrifice, or a Svarjit, or a Gosava; or with an Abhijit or a Vishvajit, or with a Trivrit Agnishtut.\"**[^1]\n\nThis verse offers these elaborate Vedic sacrifices as alternatives to other penances like living twelve years in a forest hut (11.72) or self-immolation (11.73). The broader chapter (11) details expiations (prāyaścitta) for sins across castes, with 11.74 specifically continuing options for the worst offense of Brahmana-slaughter.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-f8b471).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 11 (full), [chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/). Note on numbering: The translation labels this as Mn_11.74 but places it in the chapter 12 file due to verse overflow from chapter 11.",
